Literal and figurative mountain climber pursuing what makes me feel most alive
📸@krissyhasacamera
CEO of @blackironnutrition/@blackirontraining

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Krissy🏔 on July 15, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, people standing, shorts and outdoors.

node.text:
This is my favorite photo of my now divorced parents. It was taken in Hawaii in 1987 when they were competing in races and triathlons together.

My parents are runners.
My dad is a runner.
I am not a runner.

Because of my parents, I started running—and racing—when I was a child and ran well into college. I ran for 15 years. Running was always my dad’s thing, but I was never bad at it. So I ran too, despite never loving it the way he does.

Running eventually became punishment when I started to deal with body image and food issues in college. I started to run to lose weight when I was 21. This completely destroyed my relationship with it and I stopped. I only occasionally ran in WODs and short sprint workouts from then on.

I started running again for the first time in 10 years in December when I had no choice while at a 10-day WFR course. I was preparing for Cotopaxi with no way or time to train, so I ran 6-12 miles a day on a mix of dirt and pavement around the property.

I liked how it made my legs and lungs feel.
It felt like movement, not punishment.
I was reminded that I once ran for fun.
It made me feel connected to my dad.

So I started occasionally jogging the downhills on my hikes after then. Then I started occasionally jogging the flat parts too.

And about a month ago, I started going on hour long runs when it was too hot to do anything longer outside. Then bumped it up to 90 minutes this week.

I have no idea where this running thing is going or where it will end up. I have no expectations other than to have a healthy relationship with it.

All I know is that when I look at this picture of my 27 year old mom and 34 year old dad together at a race, I feel deeply connected to this version of them.

This picture tells me to run, so I am just going to keep running for the right reasons and see what happens.🏃🏼‍♀️

node.text:
I put the scale away and stopped weighing myself in May. I did this because—despite what many think—an increase in body weight doesn’t matter if performance and health aren’t suffering. (I will die on this hill).

I thought it would be better for my training brain if I was unaware of my weight for a while. And I was 100% correct. My climbing, hiking, lifting, and running all improved once I was entirely unaware of and unconcerned with my weight. Even when I knew I was likely gaining a little from eating more in order to train more.

I knew I was gaining throughout June for 2 reasons...
1️⃣ people started asking me if I was when I shared pictures of my body on here
2️⃣ my short liners and sports bras started to feel snugger by the week

But I stayed off the scale for nearly 6 weeks and didn’t view any of the above as bad. I kept doing what I was doing: eating lots and training hard. Because it works for me.

Then I was unexpectedly asked to step on a scale at the doctor’s office recently and couldn’t bring myself to not look…

Not only have I gained weight, but I’m also 1kg over my 72kg weight class from when I was a competitive powerlifter... as an endurance athlete.🤯

For years now, I have been told lighter is better when it comes to uphill and vertical sport. And have been told that I could be much better in all my sports if I was smaller.

Let me tell ya, I am so happy that I haven’t listened to any on these fucking people (all men) and have focussed on what matters rather than try to be smaller by eating less and not adequately fueling my body.

I started tracking my food and prioritizing my nutrition again this week for my own health. Rather than trying to lose the small amount of weight I’ve gained by restricting calories, I’m embracing it. Because this body is capable of some seriously rad shit right now and a few extra pounds aren’t weighing me down.

Be well ❤️🌮 (and think about staying off the damn scale)

Training video dump and wrap up from the week 🧗🏼‍♀️🏋🏼‍♀️🥾

I started leading 5.9, my lifts felt solid, and I got a good mix of both climbing and cardio in. Celiac disease and thunderstorms had other plans for us on Friday tho. So instead of a 13-15 hour car-to-car summit push in the mountains with busted guts and a looming storm, we stayed in Mammoth for the weekend and enjoyed some low stress climbing with friends. (Celiac disease sucks butt sometimes, I just try not to complain about it on here because people live with FAR worse).

Pretty mellow week of maintaining my current fitness level since I felt sick for a lot of it👇🏻

MON: AM-🏋🏼‍♀️ lifting / PM-🥾step-ups
TUE: AM-🚴🏼‍♀️ long stationary bike ride
WED: AM-🏋🏼‍♀️ lifting / PM-🏃🏼‍♀️run
THUR: AM- 🧗🏼‍♀️3h sport climbing
FRI: PM- 🧗🏼‍♀️4h sport/trad climbing + hiking
SAT: 💎Crystal Crag climb (first video)
SUN: REST

The plan this week is to cook all my own food so my guts  are 100% for my next big adventure in a little over a week!

node.text:
What we dislike (and why) makes us just as interesting as what we like, in my opinion. So here are 10 random well-liked things I happen to strongly dislike (and why) to help you get to know me better—or decide you don’t like me and/or want to fight me should you take any of this personally 🤣😘
 
1️⃣ Halloween. I don’t like spooky anything, I don’t do costumes, and I don’t like scary decorations.
2️⃣ Country music. Unless it’s years older than me, I find it to be truly awful.
3️⃣ Disneyland. As an adult, it’s my hell on earth. An expensive place to wait in lines.
4️⃣ Motorcycles. Too loud and/or fast! I prefer slow, quiet danger.
5️⃣ Friends (the sitcom). Too cheesy and I can’t stand Ross. I prefer It’s Always Sunny.
6️⃣ The Bachelor/Bachelorette. No need to explain.
7️⃣ Licorice of any kind. It’s so bad! How do people eat it? I gag even thinking about it!
8️⃣ Scary movies of any kind. Why do people like being horrified and/or watching fucked up shit?
9️⃣ Caves, long tunnels, or anywhere else dark and snug that could kill me.
🔟 Music festivals. So. Many. People. Everywhere. And usually fucked up. This is the opposite of fun.

And there you have me in a nutshell!

Now tell me something well-liked that you don’t like👇🏻

node.text:
Training wrap up + photo/video dump from the week 🧗🏼‍♀️🏋🏼‍♀️🥾 Climbed some hard and fun shit with all my favorite people this week and unexpectedly led my first on-sight sport climb last night!! Pretty stoked on how training is going and I’m feeling overall healthy, strong, and fast (thanks to lots of 🌮 and 💤).

This was week 3 of dialing lifting back to twice a week to make more room for both climbing and endurance training. I thought I was going to have a hard time with this given I’ve been lifting 3-6 days a week for what feels like my entire life haha (19 years). But I absolutely noticed a big difference in both my climbing and endurance this week, so I think it’s safe to say this plan is physically working well so far. Mentally, climbing and hiking seem to “do it for me” far more than lifting does these days, so turns out lifting twice a week isn’t so bad after all!

I was off my training schedule again because of friends and life, but I still got it all in for the most part (minus sprints)👇🏻

MON: PM-🏋🏼‍♀️ 1h lift (skipped morning sprints)
TUE: AM-🏃🏼‍♀️7mi run / PM-🥾1k step ups w/ pack
WED: 🧗🏼‍♀️🥾 5h of climbing + hiking
THUR: REST
FRI: AM-🏋🏼‍♀️ 1h lift / PM-🧗🏼‍♀️1.5h sport climb
SAT: AM-🥾6mi, 2k vert hike / PM-🧗🏼‍♀️4h sport climb
SUN: 🧗🏼‍♀️gym bouldering + 🚣🏼‍♀️ row workout

SHORT TERM GOALS:
1️⃣ Attempt a big car-to-car alpine climb next week with @benharclerode and @jnam06
2️⃣ Attempt a 3 day Wonderland Trail jaunt in 2 weeks with @littlelyssfitness
3️⃣ Keep getting stronger and fast for bigger alpine climbs this summer/fall with @benharclerode
4️⃣ Build miles for a 4-5 day TRT jaunt in Sep or Oct with myself

Hope you had a good week, both in training and in life! I’m a bit overwhelmed in the life department myself, but this is part of why I move my body! Be well! ❤️

#krissytrains
@blackirontraining
@blackironnutrition

node.text:
My driving privilege was taken away on 4.22.19 because I was having anxiety attacks so severe, they were mimicking seizures. I let these episodes go on in secret for 10 weeks in 2019 before Ben finally took me to the ER in April, as we had no idea that what was happening was anxiety induced quite yet.

I was admitted to the hospital then scanned and tested for multiple days in a row by doctors, nurses, and neurologists. To my relief, they determined my episodes were non-epileptic. I was sent home with anxiety meds and a referral to a psychiatrist.

Right before I left, a neurologist at the hospital stripped me of my driving privilege despite the non-epileptic mental health diagnosis. I sorta felt like I was being punished, but I understood and put up no fight. I was meant to undergo a 90-day medical suspension, then start driving again right away with no restrictions or follow ups, assuming the episodes stopped. Which they did.

Instead, I’ve been bouncing between GPs, neurologists, psychiatrists, and DMV appointments for follow up after follow up for 2 years. Repeatedly explaining my mental and physical health in detail to allll types of people in order to be able to drive, which I wasn’t allowed to for a long time.

It has been embarrassing, invasive, and completely absurd to go through this for 2 years when all I did was have anxiety attacks in my own bed during a time I was unwell. I have worked very hard to take care of myself the last 2 years via medication and various forms of therapy, but I have not been able to fully heal from that time in my life due to dealing with this since.

After waiting 4 months for an appointment with a new neuro (after finding a new GP who listens), I saw him yesterday. He actually listened to me as he ran through tests and by the end of the appointment, he told me I am more than fit to drive and that he can’t believe this is happening. Then he suggested my full driving freedom back to the DMV with no more follow up appointments or restrictions.

*Finally*

I wrote this semi-embarrassing post because I need you to take care of yourself, mentally and physically. As well as advocate for yourself when the time comes. Be well.❤️

Training wrap up in the caption + training photo/video dump from the week 🧗🏼‍♀️🏋🏼‍♀️🥾 #krissytrains

(I fell off making these posts, but I am back on bc I know you like them and I also truly like making them)

This past week was WHACK for training. I was way off my schedule due my birthday, work, the fundraiser hike, and my jaw situation (thanks again for all the recs). I’ll be back on schedule tomorrow. Here’s what training looked like, even though this is not *the best* representation of how I typically train.👇🏻

MONDAY: 🧗🏻33 laps at the climbing gym for my 33rd birthday (woof, RIP hands)
TUESDAY: Rest due to jaw pain
WEDNESDAY: 🚴🏼‍♀️1h indoor cycling intervals + 🧗🏻2h of multi pitch trad climbing
THURSDAY: 🏋🏼‍♀️ 1h of super duper light lifting
FRIDAY: 🥾33mi + 4600’ vert hike
SATURDAY: BHRD (big honking rest day)
SUNDAY: 🏋🏼‍♀️ 1h @reps4recovery group workout + 🧗🏻2h of sport climbing later today

SHORT TERM GOALS:
1️⃣ To be as fit and fast as possible for alpine climbing season these next 4 months.
2️⃣ To keep trail miles high in prep for the Wonderland Trail in 3 weeks with Lyss.
3️⃣ Due to the ongoing heat here, I’m not sure when my TRT attempt will be. Me thinks me pushes it to when its cool again so I can train hard for the 4 day (42mi x4) attempt opposed to the 5 day (34mi x5) in the fall. I need to do more mental training in order to be able to do this alone.
4️⃣ Also maybe thinking about an ultra race 🤷🏼‍♀️ (I partially blame @littlelyssfitness for this)

LONG TERM GOAL: Denali is 11 months away

Happy Sunday and kick ass this coming week! I hope you are setting big goals for yourself (they do not have to be physical), because you deserve it!! 🤗♥️

I hiked 33mi solo yesterday. For myself and for addiction recovery awareness. This is the farthest I’ve hiked in a day. The hardest part was being alone.

I semi-slacked on getting miles in to prepare for this, but I believed in my body’s ability to handle 33mi + 4600’ of vert at my current fitness level. What I did not fully believe in, was my ability to mentally do it alone with zero support anywhere along the way. Just me, the contents of my 14L pack, and 33mi of dirt and rock.

I turned around at mile 8 despite my great pace, walking back to the car out of self-doubt and not having anyone to talk to. I walked for a minute, then changed my mind. And decided that I am fully capable of doing hard shit alone, even when I don’t want to.

I did shockingly awesome from miles 10-26, physically and mentally.

I began to slowly deteriorate around 1:30pm when it got REAL hot at the same time my ankles and hips started to get achy. It was at mile 28.5 that I completely fell apart. I threw up, sat down, and damn near had a full freak out.

I called Ben crying to tell him I didn’t know how I could walk another 4.5mi alone. He gave me a pep talk, I stopped crying, then I laid down for 40min on the side of the trail in the shade and snoozed. (I made a story highlight of all this if you missed it).

I got up and slow walked 4.5 miles to the trailhead even though I deemed it impossible. It was not impossible, my mind was just telling me it was. All I had to do was not listen and keep going. I kept repeating “you got this, girl” to myself out loud the last two miles until I was done.

This adventure of course ended up representing my 8yrs in recovery. Highs and lows all over the place. Messy. Self doubt. Feeling alone. Feeling scared. Feeling proud. Feeling on top of the world. Almost quitting a few times. Not giving up when it gets hard.

It was a whole mess of trail magic that my soul needed.

THANK YOU to everyone who has donated to @reps4recovery and who has cheered me on this week. When all those DMs rolled in when it got hard yesterday, I knew I could keep going. Thank you so much for supporting me from afar.

The fundraiser will end tomorrow!

I turn 33 years young today 🥳 TW: caption discusses addiction + mental illness

It’s my birthday, but I’m unfortunately dealing with a mental/physical illness combo right now, therefore I decided at 4am that it’s in my best interest to push the 33mi fundraising trail run we had planned today to tomorrow given how much pain my head is in (I’m severely jaw clenching from anxiety). So I’m going to take care of myself today, hang with my loved ones, and try for 33mi tomorrow!

I am raising $3300 for @reps4recovery today/tomorrow. That’s what I would like for my 33rd birthday and why I’m walk-running 33 miles, the farthest I’ve ever gone on foot in one day.

In addition to raising funds, I would also like to raise awareness. In honor of recently hitting 8yrs in recovery, here are 8 facts about addiction, alcoholism, substance abuse, and mental illness👇🏻

1️⃣ Addiction and alcoholism kill tens of thousands of Americans every year, impacting millions of lives. If you personally don’t suffer from either, someone you know and love probably does.
2️⃣ Addiction is not a choice. It is a mental disorder which compels someone to repeatedly use/abuse substances despite knowing the harmful consequences.
3️⃣ Substance abuse destroys marriages, friendships, and careers, while also threatening a person’s basic health, well-being, and safety.
4️⃣ Around 21mil Americans struggle with addiction to at least one substance, yet only 10% receive treatment.
5️⃣ Roughly 15mil Americans struggle with alcoholism which causes around 88,000 to die each year.
6️⃣ There is a strong correlation between addiction and mental illness. About 30% of Americans with a mental illness also live with addiction.🙋🏼‍♀️
7️⃣ About 20% of Americans with depression or an anxiety disorder suffer from addiction, and people with bipolar disorder are 5x more to have a substance use problem.🙋🏼‍♀️
8️⃣ Out of 42.1mil people with mental illness, 18.2% live with a co-occurring substance use disorder .🙋🏼‍♀️

If you have the ability to donate today, I suggest donating $8 or $33 in honor of my 8 years in recovery or my 33 years on earth. Or whatever the heck you can/want!
THANK YOU!

Two years ago today—the day before my 31st birthday when this photo was taken—I did something completely insane on a trip to the Swiss Alps. Something most people never do in their lifetime.

I woke up.

I realized that I wasn’t living a life true to me, but rather one expected of me by others.

I realized I was leaving big dreams unfilled in the pursuit of making as much money as possible.

I realized I existed to work and that much about my career at the time was mentally unhealthy.

I realized that despite being labeled as a successful entrepreneur, I felt like I had failed myself.

I realized that I felt completely dead inside when home in Reno with 5 businesses in 3 warehouses.

I realized my urges to relapse were due to constantly feeling overwhelmed by working too much.

I realized I wasn’t letting myself be happy because I was unhappy with the life I had built and path I was on.
 I realized I was running away from the 60-70 hour work weeks I created for myself, then feeling guilty for it.

I realized I wasn’t traveling, but rather going on overpriced vacations to prove my success to others.

I realized I don’t need to be rich do all the things I want to do if I work hard enough to learn certain skills.

I realized that if I removed things from my plate, I might have less money but I’d have more time.

I realized that I only get one shot at this living thing and I needed to change a lot in order to truly live.

I realized that truly living isn’t working as much as possible to make as much as possible.

I realized that my time on this planet is mine and that I get to do WHATEVER THE FUCK I want with it.

So I pulled the rug out from underneath myself. It took me two months to do it publicly, but I did it. I got rid of a business that I didn’t align with. Then another. Then another. And changed everything about my life. I replaced the nothingness I felt with things that make me feel truly alive. Things like mountaineering, alpine climbing, and long distance hiking with the people I love most.

Two years ago today, I woke up.
And I’m so glad I did.
#betterthanabirthday

I cried alone in the tent for an hour soon after this picture was taken on May 28th. It was Ben’s 35th birthday on earth and my 8th birthday in recovery for drug addiction and substance abuse. It was the first time in 8 years I didn’t fundraise, make an over the top post about how great recovery is, or make the day entirely about me.

I wasn’t crying that May 28th finally got to be about Ben, that made me very happy. I was crying alone in the tent because recovery is hard, lonely, nonlinear, messy, and misunderstood. I was crying because I wish I could come on here and tell everyone that it keeps getting easier each year… but I can’t lie like that, ya know?

I wish I had more inspirational words to share about addiction and recovering from it, but all I have are honest words…

The truth is that recovery has gotten harder each year due to a combination of loneliness, anxiety/depression, and self-boredom. As it’s gotten harder, I’ve gotten more extreme with my goals in an effort to not drink/use because this method is working quite well for me. Doing hard physical things—occasionally alone—keeps me off drugs and away from alcohol. Most of my hobbies are physical by design, as they don’t mix well with substances the way many of my more artistic hobbies do.

Recovery is hard, takes ongoing work, and can really suck. But it’s not ALWAYS hard and it doesn’t suck nearly as much as using. When I compare the two lifestyles—my current one and my old one—recovery wins by a landslide. Even when recovery/sobriety is the harder, scarier choice… it is still the best one!!

If you are struggling, find something better than substances to get consumed by. If you love someone who is struggling, help them find something else to get wrapped up in. Climbing, lifting, hiking, and photography are the four things that work best for me.

Happy belated 8th birthday to me🍾(it’s sparkling cider, not champagne)
